occurrences.line_text: It is a darksome delue farre vnder ground,
From farre espide the famous Britomart,
Was from those Dames so farre and so vnfitting,
And she so farre astray, as none can tell.
And each not farre behinde him had his make,
Like three faire branches budding farre and wide,
Farre vnder ground from tract of liuing went,
Farre from the view of Gods and heauens blis,
That made them dreaded much of all men farre and nie.
To barre the prease of people farre away;
That in the same she farre exceld all other.
Yet did the workmanship farre passe the cost:
Into an heard, farre from the husband farme,
Vnluckie Mayd to seeke him farre and wide,
Not farre away, not meete for any guest
That he which was the last, the first did farre exceede.
Farre passing Bronteus, or Pynacmon great,
Whiles thus they communed, lo farre away
Beheld, whereas he stood not farre aside,
I cal'd her loud, I sought her farre and neare;
Vnto his caue farre from all peoples hearing,
Full fast she flies, and farre afore him goes,
That by his grenning laughter mote farre off be rad.
A litle cotage farre away they spide,
Shooting forth farre away two flaming streames,
Into the lookers hart, and killeth farre away.
Whom when the Briton Prince a farre beheld
But they so farre from peace or patience were,
And farre renowmed through exceeding fame;
But farre away from these, another sort
Farre from all fraud, or fayned blandishment;
Whose goodly workmanship farre past all other
Farre passing that, which by surpassing skill
Yet farre and neare the Nymph his mother sought,
These marched farre afore the other crew;
Whose fruitfull seede farre passeth those in land,
Is farre from hearing of my heauy plight;
Is wandred farre from where it first was pight,
Out of their proper places farre away,
To wend with her. So thence him farre she brought
Full farre was I from thinking such a pranke;
The time and place was blazed farre and wide;
So farre he past amongst his enemies band,
Or being carried farre from forraine lands.
Not farre in sea; of which the one appeares
A rout of many people farre away;
I heard report that farre abrode did fly,
But like a sort of sheepe dispersed farre
Not farre away, but little wide by West,
Yet fled she fast, and both them farre outwent,
He could aduance, he farre was gone and past.
There let her wonne farre from resort of men,
With her, to see her Ladie thence no farre away.
A straunge aduenture, which not farre thence lay;
Which wonned in a rocke not farre away,
Is wondrous strong, and hewen farre vnder ground
Those Nations farre thy iustice doe adore:
Farre thence from forrein land, where they did dwell,
They came vnto a Citie farre vp land,
On which that cursed Idole farre proclamed,
Sith ye thus farre haue tendred my poore case,
And farre away, amid their rakehell bands,
But ere he marched farre, he with them met,
There wayting for the Tyrant, till it was farre day.
He had not passed farre vpon the strand,
Which doe all worldly riches farre excell,
Its now so farre from that, which then it was,
Who seeing him from farre, with piteous sound
Not farre from hence, vppon yond rocky hill,
They saw that Carle from farre, with hand vnblest
A tall young man from thence not farre away,
Now farre from harbour likely to be lost,
Farre in the forrest by a hollow glade,
In seeking all the woods both farre and nye
For nought but woods and forrests farre and nye,
The which through fame should farre be magnifide,
The good Sir Bruin, growing farre in yeares;
The good Sir Calepine, that farre was strayd,
He sought him farre and neare, yet him no where he spyde.
He rides (said Turpine) there not farre afore,
The gentle Prince not farre away they spyde,
Thence passing forth, not farre away he found,
Vnto a litle groue not farre asyde,
They prayd high God him farre from them to send.
So farre the meane of shepheards to excell,
Although his quest were farre afore him gon;
Was farre forth spent, discoursing diuersly
Of his rich mould, did thrust it farre away,
Be farre fro me, to whom ye ill display
Who on the other side did seeme so farre
Or wanton squirrels, in the woods farre sought,
Yet she all other countrey lasses farre did passe.
So farre as doth the daughter of the day,
So farre doth she in beautyfull array,
That when thy glory shall be farre displayd
They chaunst, vpon an hill not farre away,
The Lord of Many Ilands, farre renound
Yet is no Fary borne, ne sib at all
How he did fashion his vntoward pace,
Did see and grieue at his bold fashion;
But th'only forme and outward fashion;
Nor s'deignfull of so homely fashion,
Dwelt simple truth in seemely fashion.
Himselfe to fashion likest Florimell,
And vncouth fashion, yet her well became;
Sir Artegall vndid the euill fashion,
It is, to fashion his owne lyfes estate,
That he should lead the daunce, as was his fashion;
Fashiond aboue within their inmost part,
Fashion'd to please the eies of them, that pas,
Like loathly Toades, some fashioned in the wast
So fashioned a Porch with rare deuice,
Or in Belphoebe fashioned to bee:
And him in euery part before her fashioned.
Whose future woes so plaine he fashioned,
A thousand thoughts she fashioned in her mind,
And in those Tapets weren fashioned
Fashioning worlds of fancies euermore
Or brutishly brought vp, that neu'r did fashions see.
Did poure into his Lemans lap so fast,
The drouping Night thus creepeth on them fast,
Whose double gates he findeth locked fast,
Forth spurred fast: adowne his coursers side
Or through alleageance and fast fealtie,
Full fast she fled, ne euer lookt behynd,
And thrise three times did fast from any bit:
He knocked fast, and often curst, and sware,
From vnder which fast trickled downe the sweat:
Which fast is tyde to Ioues eternall seat?
But got his ready steed, and fast away gan ride.
A Lyon spyes fast running towards him,
And turning backe, gan fast to fly away,
So fast he carried her with carefull paine,
More greedy they of newes, fast towards him do crosse.
Could not for sorrow follow him so fast;
Fast flying from the Paynims greedy pray,
No faith so fast (quoth she) but flesh does paire.
Where fast embard in mightie brasen wall,
Whose gates he found fast shut, ne liuing wight
No gate so strong, no locke so firme and fast,
Came running fast to greet his victorie,
And you fresh bud of vertue springing fast,
That fast was lockt, but key found not at all
She flying fast from heauens hated face,
Then those two knights, fast friendship for to bynd,
An armed knight towards them gallop fast,
The Redcrosse knight toward him crossed fast,
For loe he comes, he comes fast after mee.
Fled fast away, halfe dead with dying feare:
In which a rustie knife fast fixed stood,
Or free his feet, that in the myre sticke fast?
Arriued there, the dore they find fast lockt;
And in her other hand she fast did hold
She held him fast, and firmely did vpbeare,
And euery sinew seene through his long fast:
But first thou must a season fast and pray,
The steely head stucke fast still in his flesh,
Striuing to loose the knot, that fast him tyes,
From which fast trickled forth a siluer flood,
Where fast it stucke, ne would there out be got:
Vpon his sunne-bright shield, and gript it fast withall.
The other foot, fast fixed on his shield,
And fast imprisoned in sieged fort.
Till fast before the king he did alight;
With doubtfull eyes fast fixed on his guest;
And chaced her, that fast from him did fly;
Doth nourish vertue, and fast friendship breeds;
Which to confirme, and fast to bind their league,
Fast by her side did sit the bold Sans-loy
Orion, flying fast from hissing snake,
And turning to that woman, fast her hent
And both her hands fast bound vnto a stake,
Full fast away, and did her quite forsake;
And both his hands fast bound behind his backe,
Hath now fast bound, me met in middle space,
Whose flying feet so fast their way applyde,
Ere on the plaine fast pricking Guyon spide
The truncked beast fast bleeding, did him fowly dight.
Whom Guyon seeing stoup, pursewed fast
Fled fast away, to tell his funerall
And fast beside, there trickled softly downe
By this she had him lulled fast a sleepe,
An armed knight, that towards him fast ran,
And fast beside him sat tumultuous Strife:
There the good Guyon he found slumbring fast
Adowne so fast, and all his armour steepe,
Fast flying, there eternall torment found,
Twixt his two mighty armes engrasped fast,
They found the gates fast barred long ere night,
And euery loup fast lockt, as fearing foes despight.
Fly fly, good knights, (said he) fly fast away
Fly fast, and saue your selues from neare decay,
And flying fast as Roebucke through the fen,
But she so fast pursewd, that him she tooke,
Her other sonne fast sleeping did oppresse,
And fast the land behind them fled away.
Some mouth'd like greedy Oystriges, some fast
There follow'd fast at hand two wicked Hags,
His light-foot beast, fled fast away for feare:
So fast as his good Courser could him beare,
No sooner thought, then that the Carle as fast
Formerly grounded, and fast setteled
And all that dreadfull Armie fast gan flye
With her false eyes fast fixed in his sight,
So held them vnder fast, the whiles the rest
Which fled so fast, that nothing mote him hold,
As fearing euill, that pursewd her fast;
But all spurd after fast, as they mote fly,
For neuer wight so fast in sell could sit,
That the fast earth affronted them so sore,
That fast she from him fled, no lesse affrayd,
And whither now he trauelled so fast:
Fast flying through this forest from her fo,
But could not stay; so fast she did foregoe,
And made him fast out of the forrest runne;
For thy, the bloudy tract they follow fast,
Which as a victour proud, gan ransack fast
To whom her louing hart she linked fast
Which fled so fast from that same foster stearne,
No need to bid her fast away to flie;
Not halfe so fast the wicked Myrrha fled
Nor halfe so fast to saue her maidenhed,
Fast flying on a Courser dapled gray,
Fast bounden hand and foote with cords of wire,
But forward gallopt fast; which when he spyde,
She bore him fast away. Which when the knight,
Tho fast her clipping twixt his armes twaine,
But fast good will with gentle curtesyes,
And now so long before the wicket fast
And shut vp fast within her prisons blind,
He found, then his false engins fast he plyde,
And cast himselfe on ground her fast besyde:
And ranne into her louers armes right fast;
They spide, where Paridell came pricking fast
And with pale eyes fast fixed on the rest,
Either fast closed in some hollow greaue,
He ran as fast, as both his feete could beare,
And now so fast his feet he did apply,
Of such deceipt, kept th'yron dore fast bard,
Or clashing heard, he fast away did fly,
Fast locked, driuen with that stormy blast,
To enter in, but found it locked fast:
Were bounden fast, that did her ill become,
Where fast infixed, whilest he sought by slight
The other halfe behind yet sticking fast,
Stood still a while, and his fast footing kept,
And did his yron brond so fast applie,
As fast as water-sprinckles gainst a rocke are dasht.
As fast as forward erst, now backward to retrate.
Ne followd on so fast, but rather sought
Which vauntage Cambell did pursue so fast,
But when they thought it fast, eftsoones it was vntide.
And fast beside a little brooke did pas
For which his faith with her he fast engaged,
And her pursu'd as fast as she did flie:
Full fast she flies, and farre afore him goes,
And follow'd fast: but when he came in sight,
The Ladies both on horse, together fast embraced.
Them follow'd fast, and them reuiled sore,
But none of them (so fast away he flew)
From day to day she woo'd and prayd him fast,
And him embracing fast betwixt them held,
The which I found sure lockt and chained fast.
Were with a snake, whose head & tail were fast co[m]byned.
Like a wood God, and flowing fast to Rhy:
To bring forth stormes, or fast them to vpbinde,
Which when his Ladie saw, she follow'd fast,
Vppon his iron coller griped fast,
Ne ought he did, but with fast fixed eies
Enlincked fast in wedlockes loyall bond,
Fast bound on euery side with iron bands,
And heaped strokes so fast on euery side,
Her warlike maides about her flockt so fast,
The Lists were closed fast, to barre the rout
Being fast fixed in her wounded spright,
Yet in my truthes assurance I rest fixed fast.
And on the ground the other fast did stand,
Fled fast into the towne, and her sole victor left.
But yet so fast they could not home retrate,
A Damzell, flying on a palfrey fast
Yet fled she fast, and both them farre outwent,
Who still from him as fast away did flie,
He ran still on, thinking to follow fast
From whom she earst so fast away did flie;
So fast away, that ere his readie speare
And followed was of him likewise full fast;
And made him backe againe as fast to fly;
Fast did they fly, as them their feete could beare,
Him when the damzell saw fast by her side,
Ran with her fast away vnto his mew,
He threw his burden downe, and fast away did fly.
But he him hunted like a Foxe full fast:
But he then tooke it vp, and held fast in his hand.
Warning him hold it fast, for feare of slights.
As fast as feete could carry them away;
The other which was entred, laboured fast
And catching her fast by her ragged weed,
For that the terme approching fast, required speed.
The tyrant thundred his thicke blowes so fast,
But byting deepe therein did sticke so fast,
Whom Calidore perceiuing fast to flie,
But Calidore did follow him so fast,
Whiles yet his foe lay fast in sencelesse sound,
He following that faire aduantage fast,
Ran after fast, to reskue the distressed mayde.
But follow'd fast the Monster in his flight:
Through woods and hils he follow'd him so fast,
In following of him, that fled so fast,
Yet by the cry he follow'd, and pursewed fast.
Vpon his throte, did gripe his gorge so fast,
A trampling steede, that with his neighing fast
They fled, and fast into the wood did get:
With which he layd about, and made them fast to flie.
Himselfe in hast he arm'd, and did him fast pursew.
And bound him fast: Tho when he vp did looke,
They downe him hold, and fast with cords do bynde,
Then bursting forth in teares, which gushed fast
With those two Carles, fled fast away, afeard
In which his loue was lost, he slept full fast,
He followed fast, and chaced him so nie,
By this the moystie night approching fast,
And many feete fast thumping th'hollow ground,
Through cowherd feare he fled away as fast,
And flyes away as fast as he can hye,
Yet holding fast twixt both his armes extended
Tho to him running fast, he did not stay
And vp to heauen his eyes fast streming threw.
When to the Caue they came, they found it fast:
But he him fast pursuing, soone approched neare.
His shield he on him threw, and fast downe held;
Against his will fast bound in yron chaine,
Where now enclosd in wooden wals full faste,
Thereon an yron lock did fasten firme and strong.
In hope some stroke to fasten on him neare;
But whosoeuer once hath fastened
And not well fastened, would not strike him strayt,
Sithens it hath infixed faster hold
But rather how she mote him faster tye.
Mongst many foes, him selfe did faster hye;
And dieted with fasting euery day,
And through long fasting woxen pale and wan,
Before they fastned were vnder her knee
And liked well, ne further fastned not,
She fastned hath her foot, which standes so hy,
For euer as they fastned it, it loos'd
Till Florimell about her fastned it.
To be this maides, with whom I fastned hand,
And eke the fastnesse of his dwelling place,
That to those fennes for fastnesse she did fly,
And fed her fat with feast of offerings,
Abusd her plenty, and fat swolne encreace
Whiles fruitfull Ceres, and Lyï¿½us fat
This fatall day, that shall I euer rew,
For whither he through fatall deepe foresight
To tell, how he had seene the Dragons fatall fall.
Tell then, ï¿½ Lady tell, what fatall priefe
If euer he transgrest the fatall Stygian lawes.
Or did his life her fatall date expyre,
From the third brunt of this my fatall brond:
For now arriued is his fatall howre,
Driuen by fatall error, here arriu'd,
And fatall birds about them flocked were,
The fatall purpose of diuine foresight,
Vnwares haue prest: for either fatall end,
Most noble Virgin, that by fatall lore
Both ioynt partakers of the fatall paine:
Him shall he make his fatall Instrument,
Where he through fatall errour long was led
At last by fatall course they driuen were
Of fatall Thebes, of Rome that raigned long,
To the three fatall sisters house she went.
Graunt this, that when ye shred with fatall knife
And secret feare, to see their fatall fine,
Phorcys, the father of that fatall brood,
And after him the fatall Welland went,
That that same former fatall wound of his
Now lesse she feared that same fatall read,
In their first flowre, before this fatall teene
The father of that fatall progeny,
Vnder her wombe his fatall sword he thrust,
Not satisfyde till on the fatall ground
This fatall chaunce, this dolefull accident,
Knowing his fatall hand by former feare;
With knife in hand, and fatally did vow,
Shall I accuse the hidden cruell fate,
Hath thee incenst, to hast thy dolefull fate?
Their times in his eternall booke of fate
He woxe dismayd, and gan his fate to feare;
And often blame the too importune fate,
But thou, sweet Babe, whom frowning froward fate
But that fiers fate did crop the blossome of his age.
What direfull chance, armd with reuenging fate,
Accusing fortune, and too cruell fate,
My selfe well wote, and mine vnequall fate;
Abide the fortune of thy present fate,
Vnmindfull of his wound, of his fate ignoraunt.
Yet sith his fate so cruelly did fall,
His life, and long good fortune vnto finall fate.
Till he surrendred Realme and life to fate.
Whom thy good fortune, hauing fate obayd,
Ne is thy fate, ne is thy fortune ill,
And his last fate him from thee take away,
Or weene by warning to auoyd his fate?
T'approue the vnknowen purpose of eternall fate.
And to my selfe, and to accursed fate
Such as him list, such as eternall fate
Me seemes I see Amintas wretched fate,
That she desyrd th'abridgement of her fate,
What stony hart, that heares thy haplesse fate,
What fortune and his fate on him will lay,
In vaine she wisht, that fate n'ould let her yet possesse.
To them ordained by eternall fate.
But Cambels fate that fortune did preuent:
Which secret fate hath in this Ladie wrought,
Yet found they none. But by what haplesse fate,
Ooraxes, feared for great Cyrus fate;
And nam'd the riuer of his wretched fate;
But who can scape, what his owne fate hath wrought?
To attribute their folly vnto fate,
And cruell heauens haue heapt an heauy fate;
His name was Guizor, whose vntimely fate
The cruell Souldan, and with dreadfull fate
Through the sad terror of so dreadfull fate,
Sonne of a King, how euer thorough fate
And oft complayn'd of fate, and Fortune oft defyde.
But to these happie fortunes, cruell Fate
With stormes of fortune and tempestuous fate,
Vntill that, whether wicked fate so framed,
Time and suffised fates to former kynd
And fates expired could renew againe,
Sith cruell fates the carefull threeds vnfould,
For feare of euill fates, but burnen euer bright.
Or what needs her to toyle, sith fates can make
Then Merlin thus; Indeed the fates are firme,
And their importune fates all satisfide:
To contract wedlock: (so the fates ordaind.)
Not so; for what the Fates do once decree,
Vnweeting of the Fates diuine decree,
That ioyd in happy peace, till fates peruerse
As when old father Nilus gins to swell
With holy father sits not with such things to mell.
So with that godly father to his home they went.
His father fierce of treason false accused,
And foster father of the Gyant dead;
Thrise happy man, said then the father graue,
But now aread, old father, why of late
Whose father Hercules in Fraunce did quell,
And happie father of faire progeny:
Arraught the rule, and from their father drew,
And sore reproch, when so her father deare
She of his father Marinell did name,
Fond Proteus, father of false prophecis,
Great father he of generation
For him the Father of all formes they call;
Ah (said she) father, I note read aright,
She of his Father Parius did name;
That is the father of fowle gealosy,
Witnesse the father of Philosophie,
Phorcys, the father of that fatall brood,
And mightie Albion, father of the bold
His father Dolon had deuiz'd of late
Who after that his monstrous father fell
The father of that fatall progeny,
And was the father of that wounded Knight,
The fearefull Lady to her father deare,
The father of the fayrest Pastorell,
In which ye father here doe dwell at ease,
And my flockes father daily doth amend it.
Giue leaue awhyle, good father, in this shore
Her father and her friends about her lying,
Her name was Claribell: whose father hight
Which when her father vnderstood, he grew
My Fathers kingdome,--There she stopt with teares;
That did presume his fathers firie wayne,
The tree of life, the crime of our first fathers fall.
Hath made sad witnesse of thy fathers fall,
But his sad fathers armes with bloud defilde,
Thy fathers and great Grandfathers of old,
His sonne king Leill by fathers labour long,
In rule succeede, and eke in fathers prayse;
The which was dew in his dead fathers dayes:
Into her fathers closet to repayre;
I in my fathers wondrous mirrhour saw,
Shall take the crowne, that was his fathers right,
Auenge his fathers losse, with speare and shield,
To liue in thraldome of his fathers foe;
From dread of her reuenging fathers hond:
Then shewing forth signes of their fathers blood,
To be the same which in her fathers hall
Begotten by two fathers of one mother,
That whilome were (as antique fathers tell)
He had three sonnes, all three like fathers sonnes,
To leaue, till to her fathers house he had her brought.
Till to that Ladies fathers house he came;
And eke with fatnesse swollen were his eyne,
His fattie waues do fertile slime outwell,
With greedy rage, and with their faulchins smot;
Eft fierce returning, as a Faulcon faire
Now like a Stag, now like a faulcon flit:
As when a Faulcon hath with nimble flight
